'''Miller's law''' can refer to three different principles.
==In communication== Miller's law, part of his theory of communication, was formulated by [[George Armitage Miller|George Miller]], Princeton Professor and psychologist.
It instructs us to [[suspension of judgement|suspend judgment]] about what someone is saying so that we can first understand them without imbuing their message with our own personal interpretations. The law states:
{{quote| text=To understand what another person is saying, you must assume that it is true and try to imagine what it could be true of.| source=[[George Armitage Miller|George Miller]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adrr.com/aa/new.htm|title=Language in Emergency MEDICINE|publisher=|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://work911.com/communication/miller.htm|title=What is Miller's Law and what is it for?|publisher=|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref>}}
==In psychology== The [[The Magical Number Seven, Plus or Minus Two|observation]], also by George Miller, that the number of objects an average person can hold in working memory is about seven,<ref name="Psych">{{cite journal | doi=10.1037/h0043158 | last=Miller | first=G. A. | ref=harv | pmid=13310704 | author-link=George Armitage Miller | year=1956 | title=The magical number seven, plus or minus two: Some limits on our capacity for processing information | journal=Psychological Review | volume=63 | issue=2 | pages=81–97 | url=http://psychclassics.yorku.ca/Miller/ }}</ref> also known as [[The Magical Number Seven, Plus or Minus Two]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://changingminds.org/disciplines/communication/articles/millers_law.htm|title=Miller's Law|website=changingminds.org|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=grANBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA75|title=Philosophy, Science, and Psychoanalysis: A Critical Meeting|first1=Simon|last1=Boag|first2=Linda A. W.|last2=Brakel|first3=Vesa|last3=Talvitie|date=8 November 2018|publisher=Karnac Books|accessdate=8 November 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ibRVHjGmCMkC&pg=PA32|title=The Foundations of Psychoanalytic Theories: Project for a Scientific Enough Psychoanalysis|first=Vesa|last=Talvitie|date=8 November 2018|publisher=Karnac Books|accessdate=8 November 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref>
==In software development== Miller's Law was formulated by Mike Beltzner and is named in respect of [[Dave Miller (Mozilla)|Dave Miller]], long-standing owner of the [[Bugzilla]] product:
{{quote|All discussions of incremental updates to Bugzilla will eventually trend towards proposals for large scale redesigns or feature additions or replacements for Bugzilla.|source=Mike Beltzner<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.gerv.net/2011/11/millers-law/|title=Miller’s Law|publisher=|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref>}}
