{{notability|Academics|date=February 2018}} {{use dmy dates|date=June 2016}} {{use Indian English|date=June 2016}} {{Infobox person | birth_date = 1957 }} '''Robert J. Zydenbos''' (born 1957, [[Toronto]]){{r|cv}} is a [[Dutch people|Dutch]]-[[Canada|Canadian]] scholar who has doctorate degrees in [[India]]n philosophy and [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]] studies. He also has a doctorate of literature from the [[University of Utrecht]] in the [[Netherlands]]. Zydenbos also studied Indian religions and languages at the South Asia Institute and at the [[University of Heidelberg]] in [[Germany]]. He taught [[Sanskrit]] at the University of Heidelberg and later taught Jaina philosophy at the [[University of Madras]] in [[India]]. Zydenbos later taught Sanskrit, [[Buddhism]], and South Asian religions at the [[University of Toronto]] in [[Canada]]. He was the first western scholar to write a doctoral thesis on contemporary Kannada fiction.
R. Zydenbos is a strong opponent to some writers, like [[Koenraad Elst]] or N. S. Rajaram, about the controversies pertaining to the [[Indo-Aryan migration|Aryan Invasion Theory]], which Zydenbos sees as driven by political motives. Zydenbos wrote review articles in the ''Journal of the American Oriental Society''. Moreover, he has written the first comprehensive Western history of Kannada literature and translated Kannada literature into both [[German language|German]] and [[English language|English]]. He also translated Dvaitin, Virasaiva, and Jaina writings from Sanskrit. He has lived in [[Mysore]], India for 17 years.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}
==Books== *''Mokṣa in Jainism, according to Umāsvāti'' (Steiner, 1983){{r|mij}} *''The Calf Became an Orphan: A Study in Contemporary Kannada Fiction'' (Institut Français de Pondichéry, 1996){{r|cbo}} *''Jainism Today and Its Future'' (Manya, 2006){{r|jtf}}
